<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<bible xml:lang="bko" backtTranslaltionDefaultLanguage="en" oxes="2.0">
  <book id="1JN" stage="Final" version="D">
    <Annotation class="History">
      <Message author="John Wimbish" created="2009-10-05 06:00:21Z" when="2009-10-05 06:00:21Z" stage="Draft">drafted by Lazarus Aplugi; keyboarded by Helena Aplugi; team revision February 2009; with advisor 31 Aug - 1 Sept 2009 (Kupang-R);</Message>
      <Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-19 06:51:53Z" when="2010-03-19 06:51:53Z" stage="Draft">Consultant checked in Kupang with Catherine Rountree by proxy with Chuck putting her questions. See separate report. 18 Mar 2010.</Message>
    </Annotation>
    <p class="Header" usfm="h">1 Yohanis</p>
    <p class="Title Main" usfm="mt">1 Yohanis<bt>1 Yohanis</bt></p>
    <p class="Title Secondary" usfm="mt2">Sasuri Yohanis ka èci<bt>Yohanis' first letter</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis suri lula-nèti Yesus Kristus<bt>Yohanis writes about Yesus Kristus</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="1" />
      <v n="1" />Ja'a suri sasuri ne, lula-nèti <span class="Italic">Lii Holo-Nori dhu Hia Mamuri.</span><bt>I write this letter about the <span class="Italic">Words which Bring Life</span>. [NOTE: typical eastern Indonesian discourse patterns have oral title before getting stuck into it. So we've set it off as a separate paragraph.]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <span class="Italic">Lii Holo-Nori dhu Hia Mamuri</span> ne, abhu mema le karèi nèti rai-haha j'aj'i. Ne'e ne, ja'a dènge angalai ja'a ladhe ngèdhi le Nèngu dènge musi madha ji'i. Ji'i tadèngi le lii Na dènge ro'a dhilu ji'i. Aa ji'i g'ag'e ngèdhi le Nèngu dènge kacui-aai ji'i unu mi. Ji'i ladhe ngèdhi Ne sèmi èèna ka,<bt>These <span class="Italic">Words which Bring Life</span> already existed beforehand from the world's beginning. Now, I and my friends have seen Him with our own eyes. We-exc have heard Him with our our own earholes. And we-exc have touched him with our own hands. We saw/watched Him in.that.way, [NOTE on discourse: Location of "Word of Life": it is put at beginning of verse because RL narratives usually start off right away with background info--Who the story is about. (CEV also sticks last Gk clause Word of Life at beginning of verse.) Also in RL narratives and worldview, it is ok (actually not just ok, but more interesting and more intriguing) to keep things partly veiled, and to talk indirectly about someone. Thus, it seems ok to stick with the Gk in not referring overtly to Jesus as the Word of Life. So no attempt has been made to overtly link The Word of Life with Jesus Christ yet (as in NLT and other translations). If s.o. doesn't get it right away, well, it is in the header. Four verbs: heard, seen, beheld, touched, CEV has only 3, combining see and beheld. KM puts see first because this is most naturally said first when trying to prove a first hand experience. It ranks higher as an evidential.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="arkhee: beginning akouoo: hear|i(1) (1) |rhoraoo:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">arkhee: beginning akouoo: hear<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>horaoo: see, catch sight of, notice heemoon: John and the other disciples, not the people getting the letter.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>theaomai: see, look at, behold, steady and deliberate gaze pselaphaoo: touch, feel, handle, grope for<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>logos: word, message zooe: life. HCE: Since the next verse picks up on "life" as something passed on to others, and drops the "word" theme, elaborating on the Word as "living" runs the paragraph into a dead end.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>LITERALLY: That which was from the beginning, which we have heard, which we have seen with our eyes, which we have looked at and our hands have touched, concerning the word of life,</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 1:1</note><v n="2" />lula Na cèu mai ètu talora aae ji'i. Uru èèna, Nèngu pea dènge Ama Na, te ngaa limuri ne Na pad'elo le ngi'u aae Nèngu mi ji'i. Nèti èèna ka, ji'i bani lole dènge miu tasa mera mia dhèu rai-haha bisa abhu mamuri mola dhu dènge boe too-lane. Te Nèngu ne <span class="Italic">Lii Holo-Nori dhu Hia Mamuri.</span><bt>because He appeared coming into our-exc midst. Previously, He lived/resided with His Father, but now He has shown Himself to us-exc. Because of that, we-exc dare to tell you-pl how humans can get true/real life that never ends. Cuz/For (elaboration) He, = <span class="Italic">Words which Bring Life</span>.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="phanerooo: be revealed, be shown, be"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">phanerooo: be revealed, be shown, be manifested, appear martureoo: testify, witness, declare, confirm<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>apaggelloo: declare, proclaim aioonios: eternal, everlasting<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>LITERALLY: And the life was revealed, and we saw and testify and declare to you the eternal life which was with the Father and was shown to us.</Message></Annotation><note reference="1:2" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 1:14</note><v n="3" />Ji'i neo peka dènge miu, aa'i-aa'i dhu ji'i ngèdhi le aa aa'i-aa'i dhu ji'i tadèngi le, sèna ka miu dènge ji'i sama-sama bisa mamuri d'ara èci. Te èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti dhu pa'èki le dènge Ama Lamatua, aa dènge Ana Na dhu Nèngu pua mai, nuka Yesus Kristus.<bt>We-exc want to tell all of you everything which we have seen, and everything which we have heard, so.that you and we can live one insides (idiom; in.unity/ harmony/ accord). Cuz (elaboration) we-inc all are already bound/linked with God and His Child whom He sent, that.is Yesus Kristus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="koinoonia: fellowship, association, communion, interaction, close"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">koinoonia: fellowship, association, communion, interaction, close relationship, have in common, be united, mutual relationship, partnership, participate with, sharing Khristou: first time in the letter, best place to introduce Jesus fully.<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>LITERALLY: That which we have seen and heard we declare also to you, that you also may have fellowship with us. And our fellowship is with the Father and with his Son Jesus Christ.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />De ji'i suri sasuri ne, sèna ka pamaho'o d'ara miu. Dènge j'ara ne'e, d'ara ji'i asa tabha karej'e kahèi.<bt>So (consequently), we-exc write this letter, to please your-pl insides. And in.that.way, our-exc insides also increase in happiness. [TEXT: Greek reading of “you-pl” rather than “we” is weak, and not followed by any recent translation. 'our' (our joy) is probably we-inclusive although some manuscripts say your joy (see note in NLT) The concept of our-inc is acheived here by having both you-pl and we-exc be happy // LEX: Greek /plerooo/ (make full, fulfill, complete, finish) is achieved here by the word /tamba/ "increase". = we were happy, but by writing this to you, you get happy and it makes us even happier. To try and force a word like "complete" together with "happy" produces a major collocational clash.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="xara: joy plerooo: make full, fulfill,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">xara: joy plerooo: make full, fulfill, complete, finish<span class="Italic">(4) (4) </span>LITERALLY: And we write these things [to you] that our joy may be complete.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu parcaya hud'i mamuri ku ètu d'ara saraa<bt>Believers must live in the light</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="5" />A'aj'a dhu Yesus lole dènge ji'i, èèna ka dhu limuri ne ji'i neo peka dènge miu. Sèmi ne'e: Ama Lamatua be'a seli eele. Bhabhelu-katub'a ciki sa abhu boe ètu Nèngu. Te Nèngu ne nuka sèmi saraa dhu heo lo'a-lo'a, dhu pab'ali boe dènge maroga ciki sa.<bt>The teaching which Yesus told us-exc, that is what now we want to tell to you-pl. It is like.this: God (+whom you know about), is exceedingly good. He doesn't have even a little bit of evil (doublet). Cuz (elaboration) He is like light which shines brightly, which doesn't have even a little bit of darkness. [EXEG to daughter translations: light = Ex. Summ: "symbolizes all ethically good qualities of God; first listed is goodness, but other credible ones include: holiness, purity, righteousness, truth; ES: What is meant by darkness'? It is the opposite of light / antithesis of all that God is -- a symbol for evil (general, deeds, way of life), untruthfulness, sin, error,]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aggelia: message, announcement phoos: light --"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">aggelia: message, announcement phoos: light -- a forced metaphor in Pidgin, not self evident<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>skotia: darkness, gloom -- also a forced metaphor LITERALLY: And this is the message which we heard from him and declare to you, that God is light and there is no darkness at all in him.<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Ladhe èdhi padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èdhi mamuri d'ara èci dènge Lamatua,&gt;&gt; aa te ngaa èdhi mamuri tao bhelu era, na, èèna sama sèmi èdhi mamuri ètu d'ara maroga. Te èdhi padhai lii kapod'e-kabèli aa mamuri madhutu boe j'ara dhu mola.<bt>If we-inc speak saying, &lt;&lt;We-inc live one insides (idiom; in.unity/ harmony/ accord) with God2,&gt;&gt; but.in.actual.fact we-inc are still living doing evil, na, that is the same as if we-inc live in the dark. Cuz (elaboration) we speak twisted-turned (idiom; deceptively), and do not live following the straight/true/correct path/way.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="peripateoo: walk around, go around, live"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">peripateoo: walk around, go around, live skotia: "da" would make it sound like a no-no list. Should be generic throughout the letters except when qualified.<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>pseudomai: lie; "bulai" is often transitive, but it has an intransitive use poieoo: do, practice<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>aletheia: truth. It needs to qualify something, rather than standing alone as a Greek abstract noun. LITERALLY: If we say that we have fellowship with him, and walk in darkness, we lie, and do not practice the truth.<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Te ngaa ladhe èdhi mamuri madhutu j'ara mola, èdhi èci èèna ka dènge dhèu dhu mamuri ètu d'ara saraa Ama Lamatua. Dènge j'ara ne, èdhi aa'i-aa'i ti bisa mamuri d'ara èci. Aa d'ara èdhi mola-mèci, lula mamadhe Yesus Kristus, Ana Ama Lamatua, aa raa Nèngu rase pamèu-mèu sasala èdhi.<bt>But if we-inc live following the straight/correct path/way, we are like people who live in God's light. In that way, we-inc can all live one insides (in.unity/ harmony/accord). And our-inc insides become clean/pure/holy (doublet), because of the death of Yesus Kristus, God's Child, and His blood has cleansed away all our-inc wrongs. [Ex. Summ.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="mèu aadha-aadha = barisi total ;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z">mèu aadha-aadha = barisi total ; rase pamèu-mèu = cuci barisi</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="phoos: light. haima: blood|i(7) (7) |rkatharizoo:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">phoos: light. haima: blood<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>katharizoo: cleanse hamartia: sins we have committed, or sins we might potentially commit too? If anterior, then "da" and "wen" are OK.<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>LITERALLY: But if we walk in the light, as he is in the light, we have fellowship with each other, and the blood of Jesus his Son cleanses us from all sin.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu mamuri ètu d'ara saraa, mamuri heka dènge tao sala [\s2]<bt>People who live in the light, do not live/keep doing wrong anymore [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="8" />Ladhe èdhi padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Èdhi tao boe sala,&gt;&gt; èèna j'aj'i tadha, peka na, èdhi tipu ngi'u èdhi unu ti, aa te'a boe mia ka dhu lèke.<bt>If we-inc speak, saying, &lt;&lt;We-inc don't do wrong,&gt;&gt; that is a sign saying, we are deceiving our own selves, and do not know what is true/correct.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="planaoo: deceive, mislead, fool, be led"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">planaoo: deceive, mislead, fool, be led astray, take the wrong road ouk estin en heemiin: is the truth absent from our thinking? our doing? how does it relate to "us"?<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>LITERALLY: If we say that we do not have sin, we deceive ourselves, and the truth is not in us.</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Te ngaa ladhe èdhi mangaku sasala èdhi, tatu Ama Lamatua dhu d'ara mola, saku eele sasala èdhi madhutu lii pajaji Na, aa Na pamèu d'ara èdhi.<bt>But If we-inc acknowledge/confess our-inc wrongs, surely God who has straight/just insides, will also wipe away our wrongs according to His promise, and cleanse our insides.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="homologeoo: confess, say the same thing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">homologeoo: confess, say the same thing about, acknowledge openly pistos: trustworthy, faithful, dependable, worthy of confidence. "God" needs to be repeated because the span for pronominal identification is different from English, and still different from Greek.<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>dikaios: just, righteous aphiemi: forgive, cancel a debt, removal of guilt. Usually phrased as a lexical doublet: let us go an take away our shame<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>katharizoo: cleanse, purify. Doesn't need a repeated auxiliary "goin", since these actions can be taken as two aspects of a single process. adikia: unrighteousness, wickedness, injustice<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>LITERALLY: If we confess our sins, he is faithful and just to forgive us our sins, and cleanse us from all unrighteousness.</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ladhe èdhi peka, na, &lt;&lt;Èdhi tao tèdhi boe sasala,&gt;&gt; sasoa na, èdhi tao Ama Lamatua dhèu leko-monya! Te Nèngu ka dhu peka tèke, na, dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu manahu asa d'ara sasala-sasigo. Aa ladhe lii padhai èdhi sèmi èèna, tadha na, Lii Holo-Nori Nèngu abhu boe ètu d'ara èdhi.<bt>If we-inc speak, saying, &lt;&lt;We have never done wrong,&gt;&gt; na, that means we have made God become a habitual twister-turner (idiom; deceiver/liar). Cuz (elaboration) He has said that everyone has fallen into wrong (doublet). And if we say that, it's a sign that, His Words are not in our-inc insides. [EXEG: Ex. Summ: "Have not sinned': The claim in 1:8 denies having a sin nature, while the claim here denies having committed sinful acts.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="heemarteekamen: any kind of sin. &quot;Da&quot;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">heemarteekamen: any kind of sin. "Da" would be too restrictive. pseustes: liar<span class="Italic">(10) (10) </span>logos: word, message LITERALLY: If we say that we have not sinned, we make him a liar, and his word is not in us.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="2" />
      <v n="1" />Ana pasue aa'i-aa'i! Ja'a suri se'e aa'i-aa'i, sèna ka miu mamuri dènge tao ia ka sasala. Te ngaa ladhe abhu dhèu dhu tao sala, èèna na abhu kahèi dhu sarii èdhi ètu madha Ama Lamatua. Dhu sarii èdhi èèna, nuka Yesus Kristus, Dhèu Mola-Mèci dhu Ama Lamatua pua mai le asa rai-haha ne.<bt>Beloved children! I write you all this, so.that you don't live doing wrong anymore. But if there is (someone) who does wrong, later there is (one) who will defend us-inc in front of Father God. The (one) who will defend us is Yesus Kristus, the Clean/Holy Person whom God has already sent into this world. [EXEG: VOCATIVES: Gk. vocatives at 1 Jn 2:1 “children” [Gk teknia] (not literally ‘little children’ [NRSV] or ‘dear children’ [NLT] although those English translations are not inconsistent with John's style); 2:7 “beloved”; 2:12 “children” [Gk teknia]; 2:13a “fathers/parents”; 2:13b “young men/people”; 2:14a “children” [Gk paidia -recent research (e.g. Nyland) is finding that this term is much broader than ‘child/lad’, and can encompass adults and females in its usage in the NT, LXX and extra-biblical Koiné uses]; 2:14b “fathers/parents”; 2:14c “young men/people”; 2:18 “children” [Gk paidia]; 2:28 “children” [Gk teknia]; 3:2 “beloved” [Gk agapetoi]; 3:7 “children” [Gk teknia]; 3:13: “brothers/brothers and sisters” [Gk adelphoi]; 3:18 “children” [Gk teknia]; 3:21 “beloved”; 4:1 “beloved”; 4:4 “children” [Gk teknia]; 4:7 “beloved”; 4:11 “beloved”; 5:21 “children” [Gk teknia]; Structure: Gk can use vocatives sentence initial, medial, or final. Lgs around Timor can only use vocatives sentence initial - except for a few fixed phrases (as in 2:28, which may not be natural in daughter lgs). Semantics and referent tracking: Gk teknia “children” really doesn't have “dear” or “little” as an inherent part of it's semantics. And just like Carson says too much should not be read into differences between Gk agapaw and philew (which are often used interchangeably), so too here I don't think we should read too much into the switch between teknia and paidia. To do so would result in overtranslation. In these lgs, to translate the Gk agapetoi “beloved” as “friends” (as in 3:2) would diminish/distance them in status and intimacy, whereas using the same term “beloved children” is closer to the force of the Gk, indicating they are really special in John's eyes. Style: My sense of these languages is that 1) John uses vocatives way more than most people in this region would; 2) the sense of plain “children” is a much more natural vocative in these lgs than heavy repetition of “dear children”; BUT 3) the repetition of “dear children” does reflect John's unique and repetitious style of writing; HOWEVER 4) while it works in Kupang (sort of), it is probably forced and heavy in many daughter lgs, so given that the Gk does not have an explicit “dear” anyway, I would support daughter translations using the lighter phrasing of just “children” in many of these places.] [NOTE: My little children: although Greek has 'my' it is more natural in KM vocatives like this to leave it implied. // LEX: KeyT: bela kotong: /paraklêtos/ appears to only appear here and in John, so no previous KM translation of it yet. // NOTE to daughter translations: Compare Righteous One in Acts 7:52.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teknion: little child. It's an old"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">teknion: little child. It's an old man writing to younger Christians whom he has been warmly encouraging for years. hamarteete: present durative. "Da" would make it sound too specific.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>parakletos: helper, intercessor, advocate, person who pleads another's cause, lawyer Khriston: the full identification here adds to the impact of the statement, and besides it's in a different rhetorical segment from the first use. But "Christ" is all that's needed in the section heading.<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>dikaios: righteous, upright, just LITERALLY: My little [dear] children, I write these things to you so that you may not sin. But if anyone sins, we have an advocate with the Father, Jesus Christ the righteous one.<span class="Italic">(1)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Nèngu madhe j'aj'i korban pala èdhi, sèna ka Ama Lamatua saku eele sasala-sasigo èdhi. Madha j'ara ne hia boe mi èdhi mesa ti di, te ngaa hia mi dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne kahèi.<bt>He died becoming a sacrifice for us-inc, so.that God wipes/ erases away our-inc wrongs. This issues is not just for us-inc ourselves, but also for all the humans in this world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hilasmos: propitiation, expiation, sin offering, sin"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">hilasmos: propitiation, expiation, sin offering, sin offering substitute, remove defilement/sin, atoning sacrifice, cleanse from defilement monos: only<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>holos: whole kosmos: world<span class="Italic">(2) (2) </span>LITERALLY: And he is the propitiation for our sins, not only for ours, but also for the whole world.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu mamuri ètu d'ara saraa, tao madhutu paredha Ama Lamatua, risi-risi paredha lula-nèti sasue [\s2]<bt>People who live in the light, do according to God's command/s, especially the command about love [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="3" />Èdhi te'a, na, èdhi tadhe mèu Ama Lamatua ladhe èdhi madhutu paredha Nèngu.<bt>We know, that, we know2 God well, if/when we-inc follow/obey His commands. [NOTE to daughter translations: "know": Ex Summ: It means to be personally acquainted with God (many say deep/intimate is implied here), It is not talking about head knowledge /tau, mangarti/. But be careful about just using a neutral term equivalent to /kanál/ by itself, (to know s.o., their character, etc.) because it can have a strong sense 1) know s.o.'s character intimately, or a weak/shallow sense 2) You can kanál someone you met only briefly. Perhaps /kanál bae/ or /ta'ika/. Avoid the /babae/ equivalent of the Romans sense of "right relationship, no damage in the relationship, because that is not in focus here.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ginooskoo: know, come to know, perceive;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">ginooskoo: know, come to know, perceive; personal intimacy and relationship implied but not asserted. teerein: keep, observe, fulfill, pay attention to<span class="Italic">(3) (3) </span>entolee: commandment LITERALLY: And by this we know that we know him, if we keep his commandments.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Dhèu bisa peka, na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a tadhe Ama Lamatua.&gt;&gt; Te ngaa ladhe nèngu madhutu boe paredha Lamatua, èèna j'aj'i mi tadha, na, nèngu dhèu kapod'e-kabèli dhu padhai lii leo tao leo.<bt>A person can speak, saying, &lt;&lt;I know God.&gt;&gt; But if s/he doesn't do according to God2's command/s, that is a sign s/he is a habitual twister-turner (=idiom; deceiver) who speaks one way, acts another way. [EXEG: the truth is not in him: Msg: his life doesn't match his words (concept "absence of truth" is implicit in 'say one thing, do another' and this is a very well known and natural KM phrase.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: The one who says, &quot;I"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: The one who says, "I know him", and does not keep his commandments, is a liar, and the truth is not in him.</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu tao madhutu paredha Lamatua, èèna j'aj'i tadha, peka na, sasue nèngu mi Lamatua èèna, dhu lèke tare'a. Dènge j'ara ne'e, èdhi te'a, na, èdhi dhèu unu Lamatua.<bt>But people who do according to God2's command/s, that becomes evidence/proof that his/her love toward God, is correct/true. In.that.way, we know, that, we-inc here, are God2's people. [LEX: "love has been perfected": to try to collocate complete /langkap/ with love /sayang/ results in a big clash. Here the concept of 'complete' is communicated by saying his love for God, is now correct/ideal (implicit: beforehand, it wasn't).]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="an: indefinite condition, &quot;If get one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">an: indefinite condition, "If get one guy..." agape: love<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>alethoos: truly, truly, actually teleiooo: make perfect, perfect, complete<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>LITERALLY: But whoever keeps his word, truly the love of God has been perfected in him. By this we know that we are in him.</Message></Annotation><v n="6" />De ladhe dhèu padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a mamuri pa'èki dènge Ama Lamatua,&gt;&gt; sasoa na, nèngu hud'i mamuri ku sama sèmi Yesus Kristus.<bt>So (consequently), if a person speaks, saying, &lt;&lt;I live bound/linked with God1&gt;&gt;, na, s/he must live like Yesus Kristus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="menw: remain, abide, continue opheilw: ought"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">menw: remain, abide, continue opheilw: ought to, must, owe something<span class="Italic">(6) (6) </span>peripatew: walk, go, go around, live, conduct LITERALLY: The one who says he remains in him ought to live just as that one lived.<span class="Italic">(6)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ana pasue aa'i-aa'i! Lii paredha dhu ja'a suri hia miu ne, j'ara hiu boe. Te paredha ne dhu suri le ètu d'ara Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua dhu miu tadèngi le karèi nèti uru ka.<bt>Beloved children! The command which I write here, is not a new thing for you-pl. Cuz (elaboration) this command has already been in God2's Words which you have already heard from long ago. [EXEG: what command he is talking about is not explicit in Greek, but it is clear that he assumes this is given/known info to the readers. Commentators agree the rabbinic/Jesus command to Love is the obvious theme. Ex. Summ.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="agapeetoi: here &quot;good friends&quot; is OK."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">agapeetoi: here "good friends" is OK. LITERALLY: Beloved, I write to you no new commandment, but an old commandment, which you had from the beginning. The old commandment is the word which you heard.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="2:7" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 13:34</note><v n="8" />Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa abhu j'ara hiu dhu ja'a neo suri lula-nèti paredha Lamatua. Lii paredha ne, j'aj'i le dènge be'a ètu d'ara mamuri Yesus. Aa paredha ne mulai sab'a le ètu d'ara miu, lula maroga ètu d'ara miu mulai ele, aa saraa dhu tare'a èèna, pasaraa le ètu d'ara mamuri miu.<bt>Even.though it's like.that, nevertheless there is a new thing which I want to write about this command of God2's. This command came into being/fruition in a good way/manner in Yesus' life. And this command has begun to work in your-pl insides, because the darkness in your insides has begun to disappear, and the true/correct light has already begun to shine in your lives.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="palin: again alethinos: genuine, real, true|i(8)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">palin: again alethinos: genuine, real, true<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>paragw: pass away, go away, take past skotia: darkness<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>phainw: shine phws: light<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>LITERALLY: Yet, I write you a new commandment, which is true in him and in you, because the darkness is going away, and the true light is already shining.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Dhèu bisa padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a mamuri ètu d'ara saraa.&gt;&gt; Te ngaa ladhe nèngu tèka d'ara dènge a'ari na, sasoa na, nèngu mamuri ètu d'ara maroga era.<bt>A person could speak, saying, &lt;&lt;I live in the light.&gt;&gt; But if s/he hates/wants revenge on his/her sibling/s, that means that, s/he is still living in the dark.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="misew: hate ton adelphon autou: brother"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">misew: hate ton adelphon autou: brother or sister, kin or association (union brothers, people on the same team). [Remark: "Gotta show dis to my cousin!"]<span class="Italic">(9) (9) </span>arti: now, at the present time, still LITERALLY: The one who says he is in the light, but hates his brother, is in the dark until now.<span class="Italic">(9)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Lula dhèu dhu mamuri ètu d'ara saraa, nèngu hud'i pasue ku dènge a'ari na, aa abhu boe bhabhelu-katub'a ètu d'ara na dhu pamanahu nèngu.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) a person who lives in the light, s/he must love his/her sibling/s, and there is no evil (doublet) at all in his/her insides which makes him/her fall. [TN, Ex. Summ.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="skandalon: trap, snare, impediment, stumbling block,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">skandalon: trap, snare, impediment, stumbling block, cause to stumble, offend, cause to sin. It doesn't say who is being fouled up, so it could be limited to the brother or sister in question. But it's more like he's not the kind of person who goes around playing games with anyone. LITERALLY: The one who loves his brother remains in the light, and there is no cause to stumble in him.<span class="Italic">(10)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="11" />Nèti èèna ka, ladhe abhu dhèu dhu tèka d'ara dènge a'ari na, èèna j'aj'i tadha, na, nèngu mamuri ètu d'ara maroga. Nèngu gogo ai lae-lae, lula maroga pabèdhu le musi madha na.<bt>That's.why, if there is a person who hates his/her sibling/s, that is a sign that s/he is living in the dark. He/She walks groping blindly, because the dark has made his/her eyes blind.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hupagw: go, go away tuphlow: make"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">hupagw: go, go away tuphlow: make blind, to blind<span class="Italic">(11) (11) </span>LITERALLY: But the one who hates his brother is in the dark, and lives in the dark, and does not know where he is going, because the darkness has blinded his eyes.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu mamuri ètu d'ara saraa, mamuri boe madhutu dad'èi rai-haha [\s2]<bt>People who live in the light, do not live following/according to the world's will/desire [personification, synecdoche] [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="12" />Ana-ana! Ja'a suri sasuri ne hia miu,<bt>Children! I am writing this letter to you-pl, [NOTE: TH: For I am writing see 2.1.-In vv. 12-13b John uses the present tense of "to write," in vv. 13c and 14 the aorist tense; the latter may be rendered also "I have written" (NEB). This variation is probably a matter of style rather than meaning. KM: uses /ada tulis/ for first set; /tulis/ for second set.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teknia: here may refer to one"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">teknia: here may refer to one segment of the group. In 2:1 and 2:18 it's the whole group, and it's possible that that could be the case here; but if it is, why are the three constructions so strongly parallel?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula Kristus madhe le gati miu,<bt>because Kristus has died replacing you,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">hèia Ama Lamatua saku eele le sasala miu.<bt>and/so God has already wiped/erased away your wrongs,</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="aphiemi: forgive dia to onoma autou:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">aphiemi: forgive dia to onoma autou: in this context, probably has to do with the fact that you are associated with him (God? Christ?[Ex. Summ leans almost exclusively to Christ]) publicly, committed to be known as his people; his name is bestowed on you. The accusative is "because of," not "through," which would be more like the genitive.<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>LITERALLY: I write to you little children, because your sins were forgiven through his name [because of him].</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="13" />Dhèu-dhèu heka! Ja'a suri sasuri ne hia miu,<bt>Old people/parents/clan elders! I am writing this letter to you, [EXEG: See Source, NCV and TranNotes and IVP Bible background re ungendered forms of terms. NOTE to daughter translations: Advantage of using /orang tua/ is it pairs nicely with /orang muda/ below; but beware of potential ambiguity. /orang tua/ has two senses 1) parents, 2) clan elders; many people in Kupang default to the second sense; they normally use /mama-bapa/ when they want to specify equiv. of Eng. "parents" CHECK]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula miu tadhe Yesus Kristus,<bt>because you-pl know Yesus Kristus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu abhu mema le karèi nèti uru ka.<bt>who already existed beforehand from long ago. [Ex. Summ #1]</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ana-ana ngèru! Ja'a suri sasuri ne hia miu,<bt>Young people! I am writing this letter to you,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula miu lab'a le bhabhelu-katub'a,<bt>because you have opposed/fought against evil (doublet)</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">toke segi.<bt>to.the.point.that you have won.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="neaniskos: youth, young man nikaw: conquer,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">neaniskos: youth, young man nikaw: conquer, overcome (needs to be parallel with 14)<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>poneros: wicked, evil LITERALLY: I write to you fathers, because you have known the one who is from the beginning. I write to you young men, because you have overcome the Evil One.<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">
      <v n="14" />Ana-ana! Ja'a suri sasuri ne hia miu,<bt>Children! I write this letter to you,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula miu tadhe Ama Lamatua.<bt>because you know Father God.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Dhèu-dhèu heka! Ja'a suri sasuri ne hia miu,<bt>Old people/parents/clan elders! I write this letter to you,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula miu tadhe Yesus Kristus,<bt>because you know Yesus Kristus,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">dhu abhu mema le karèi nèti uru ka.<bt>who already existed beforehand from long ago.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 1" usfm="q1">Ana-ana ngèru! Ja'a suri sasuri ne hia miu,<bt>Young people! I write this letter to you,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">lula miu tèka le Lii Holo-Nori ètu d'ara miu,<bt>because you have stored/put.away God2's Words in your insides,</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">toke miu j'aj'i èra,<bt>to.the.point. that you have become strong.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èra pètu-pètu, = gesit, trampil, skillful"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z">èra pètu-pètu, = gesit, trampil, skillful</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">aa miu lab'a le bhabhelu-katub'a,<bt>and you have opposed/fought against evil (doublet),</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 3" usfm="q3">toke miu segi.<bt>to.the.point that you have won.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="The verse division of Nestle 26"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">The verse division of Nestle 26 makes a lot more sense than chopping up perfectly good poetry lines like Chinese chicken, RSV style. paidia: child, taken as synonymous with teknia,. It's actually the same word Jesus uses to address his friends in John 21:5, "Hey guys," "Hey pals"<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>isxuros: strong, mighty, powerful, physical strength nenikeekate: needs to be parallel with 13, one way or the other<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>LITERALLY: I write to you, children, because you have known the Father. I write to you fathers, because you have known the one who is from the beginning. I write to you young men, because you are strong and the word of God remains in you, and you have overcome the Evil One.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="15" />Miu baku sue dad'èi rai-haha, dènge mèdha-panyau na. Te dhèu dhu sue rai-haha, bisa boe sue Ama Lamatua.<bt>You don't love the desires of the world [personification], and/nor its possessions/wealth. Cuz (elaboration) a person/people who loves the world, cannot love God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ton kosmon: this is the world"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">ton kosmon: this is the world as the impermanent place whose inhabitants don't care about God, not the beautiful world of surf and sunsets and people. "Dis world" plugs into the impermanence. The reason for not loving it is not because it's inherently bad, because it isn't; but because it's the place where people do bad things, and it isn't going to be around forever. But the passage itself doesn't really address what characteristics of it we are not supposed to get enamored with. ta en tooi kosmooi: in, not from (contrasts with ek in v. 16)<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>LITERALLY: Do not love the world, or the things in the world. If anyone loves the world, love for the Father is not in him.</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Madha j'ara dhu abhu ètu rai-haha ne, pa'èki boe dènge Ama Lamatua. Nuka sèmi, dhèu dhu mamuri pakarej'e dhoka ngi'u na; dhèu manga'a; aa dhèu dhu d'èi padedha iisi lula kakaja-sasu'i na. J'ara sèmi se'e se mai boe nèti Ama Lamatua, te ngaa mai dhoka nèti rai-haha di.<bt>Things which are in this world are not bound/linked with God. For example, a person/people who lives making his/her own self happy (implicit: not caring about others); greedy person/people; and a person who likes to elevate themselves (=idiom; proud/arrogant) because of his/her riches (doublet). Things (non-concrete) like that do not come from God, cuz (elaboration) they come only from this world.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hoti: &quot;You know&quot; helps tie 16"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">hoti: "You know" helps tie 16 and 17 together alazoneia: pretension, pride, insolence, display; ostentation, make tantaran, big show, big noise? inherently looked down on. The other things need an "ony" to make them sound bad because they're selfish.<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>bios: life, means of staying alive, style of living LITERALLY: Because all that is in the world, the lust of the flesh and the lust of the eyes, and the pride of life, is not from the Father, but is from the world.<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Aa te ngaa rai-haha ne bèli-camèd'a ele, palere-lere dènge ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu dhèu neo unu. Te ngaa dhèu dhu d'èi madhutu dad'èi Ama Lamatua, dhèu ne ele boe, te nèngu mamuri toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>Whereas in fact, this world will later disappear away, together with those things which people want to own/obtain. But the person who likes/desires to do according to God's will, that person will not disappear, cuz (elaboration) s/he will live forever.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And the world passes away,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And the world passes away, and its lusts, but the one who does the will of God remains forever.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu mamuri ètu d'ara saraa mage pamud'e, sèna ka baku lèke tipu [\s2]<bt>People who live in the light must be careful so (they) don't get deceived [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ana-ana! Lod'o-lod'o èle rai-haha ne oe d'ai kèna. Miu tadèngi le, peka na, dhèu dhu lab'a Kristus, bèli-camèd'a cèu mai. Madhutu iia-iia na, rèngu mai le. Te ètu mia-mia, abhu le dhu lab'a Kristus. Se'e se j'aj'i mi tadha, na, lod'o-lod'o èle rai-haha ne dètu ae le.<bt>Children! The final (end of world) days are already imminently near. You-pl have already heard that people who oppose Kristus will later appear. Whereas in fact they have already come. Cuz (elaboration) there already are those who opppose Kristus all over the place. These are signs that the final days are already imminently near. [EXEG: see Nyland, CEV, Ex. Summ #2; note the Gk has no article, so the idea of The Antichrist (as a single specific person) is based on external assumptions, not textual clues from the Gk in this passage; NOTE to daughter translations: /Kristus pung musu/ or /yang malawan sang Kristus/ is a good match for the Gk. being unmarked for number and not specific.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="paidia: by now, &quot;you guys jalike"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">paidia: by now, "you guys jalike my kids" has been beaten to death. Now that he's back to the whole group, we need a more relaxed way of addressing them. And since paidia can be used among adult peers, not just Greek speaking children, let's use a Pidgin phrase appropriate for adult peers. John is keeping his leader-of-the-group stance, in any case. antikhristos: no article; not a name but the characterization of a type<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>LITERALLY: Little children, it is the last hour. And just as you have heard that the Antichrist is coming, even now there are many antichrists. By that we know that it is the last hour.</Message></Annotation><note reference="2:18" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">2 Tesalonika 2:1-12</note><v n="19" />Dhèu palab'a sèra cèu nèti talora aae èdhi. Te ngaa rèngu se dhèu èdhi boe. Te, ladhe rèngu tare'a-re'a dhèu èdhi, tatu ra tèke eele boe èdhi, te ngaa ra taha taruu dènge èdhi. Aa te ngaa rèngu rai aa'i le nèti èdhi. De lèke tare'a, rèngu se dhèu èdhi boe, si?<bt>Those opposers appeared from our-inc midst. However they were not our-inc people. Cuz (elaboration) if they really were our people, surely they wouldn't go away abandoning us, but they would keep persevering/enduring together with us. But in fact they all fled from us. So (consequently), it's clear that they were/are not our people, right?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: They went out from us,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: They went out from us, but they were not of us. Because if they had been of us, they would have remained with us. But [they went out] so that it might be clear that they were not all of us.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Te ngaa miu sama boe sèmi rèngu. Te miu dhu sèmi mere le Roh nèti Dhèu Mola-Mèci Ama Lamatua. Aa Nèngu soru-bara le miu, sèna ka me'a mèu ngaa dhu lèke.<bt>But you-pl are not like them. Cuz (elaboration) you have already received God's Holy Person's Spirit. And He has already helped (doublet) you, so that you understand what is true/correct. [EXEG: Ex. Summ. Annointing: IVP Bible Background: Many commentators hold that the “anointing” (v. 27) is the Spirit (cf. Jn 14:17, 26; Acts 10:38); // Annointing: See Key Biblical Terms 'anoint' for this verse and verse 27. Seems important to not just leave annointing as 'power' kuasa, because that is a cliche and the point here is power to discern spiritual things, not power to boss people around. (could make explicit Holy Spirit gives power to understand) // 'you know (what is true)': TN, NIV, TEV, LB. // TEXT: "you all" vs. "all things" GNT indicates a high degree of doubt. Alf, My, KJV, and NAB. TB, CEV, Source, NLT go for "you all". So do we.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But you have an anointing"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But you have an anointing from the Holy One, and you know all things/all of you have knowledge.</Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Miu pangee, na, ja'a suri sasuri ne'e, lula ja'a pangee, na, miu me'a boe ngaa dhu lèke, do? Aad'o! Te miu me'a mèu le mia ka dhu lèke, aa mia ka dhu leko-monya.<bt>Do you-pl think that I write this letter, because I think/assume/guess that you-pl don't know what is true/correct? No! Cuz you already understand which (of options) are true/ correct, and which are twisted-turned (idiom; deceptive).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ouk egrapsa: negative scope is tricky"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">ouk egrapsa: negative scope is tricky -- not "I didn't write" but "the reason I did write was not...". Also epistolary aorist. paan pseudos: categorical, not specific lies. But he's leading up to the Big Lie in verse 22. Pinning down lies in general is better accomplished by "Kay den" in 22, not by making 21 more specific than it is.<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>LITERALLY: I have not written to you because you do not know the truth, but because you know it, and because no lie is of the truth.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sèna ka tao miu dhu me'a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z">sèna ka tao miu dhu me'a boe ngaa dhu lèke, do?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="22" />Madhutu mola-mola na, abhu le ètu rai-haha ne dhèu kapod'e-kabèli. Tasamia sèna ka èdhi tadhe si? Rèngu sèra, nuka dhèu dhu padhai lii, peka na, Yesus èèna Kristus boe. Madhutu a'abhu rèngu, Yesus èèna, Dhèu Mola-Mèci boe, dhu Lamatua pajaji tèke hia mai. Dhèu dhu padhai lii sèmi sèra palab'a dènge Kristus, te rèngu tule eele Ama Lamatua dènge Ana Na.<bt>Actually, there are habitual deceivers/con artists (doublet) in this world. How can we know/recognize them? They are people who speak saying, Yesus [+known info], is not Kristus. According to them, Yesus is not the Clean/Holy Person whom God2 promised beforehand to send. People who speak like.that, are (actively, wilfully) opposing Kristus, cuz (elaboration) they reject Father God and His Child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="arneomai: deny, repudiate, disown someone, reject."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">arneomai: deny, repudiate, disown someone, reject. This is a verbal action, usually rejection of a person, not denial of a proposition, except when used with "hoti" as in the first part of 22. LITERALLY: Who is the liar, except the one who denies that Jesus is the Christ? He is the antichrist, the one who denies the Father and the Son.<span class="Italic">(22)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Dhèu dhu tule eele Ana Ama Lamatua, rèngu tule eele Ama Na kahèi. Te ngaa ladhe dhèu mangaku Ana Ama Lamatua, sasoa na, dhèu sèra j'aj'i le ana-ana Ama Lamatua.<bt>People who reject Father God's Child, na, they also reject His Father. But if people acknowledge God's Child, that means they also have become God's children. [NOTE to daughter translations: Unlike KM, many vernaculars cannot /mangaku/ s.t. positive in the sense of "affirm, acknowledge" (Jesus Christ as Lord). They can only /mangaku/ "sins". It is a tight collocational restriction. Be sure to CHECK it out carefully, and watch out for the translators wanting to use it just because it is in the Kupang.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="juku = tola (push away slightly)"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z">juku = tola (push away slightly)</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="arnoumenos ... homologoon: both speech acts;"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">arnoumenos ... homologoon: both speech acts; the ensuing actions are not in focus right here. If we tried to work in "say dat Jesus da Spesho Guy God Wen Send" to keep it locked in with 22, it should be "say dat God's Boy, he da Spesho Guy God Wen Send" in order not to violate John's switch of terms. But that begins to sound like a tautology, and misses the fact that John has moved away from a clause with hoti to a plain accusative. LITERALLY: Everyone who denies the Son does not have the Father. The one who confesses the Son has the Father too.<span class="Italic">(23)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="24" />De miu hud'i kèpe ku pa'èra-èra ngaa dhu miu tadèngi mere le karèi nèti uru sèra. Dènge j'ara ne'e, miu pa'èki taruu dènge Ama Lamatua, aa dènge Ana Na kahèi.<bt>So (consequently), you-pl must hold firmly to what you have heard from that prior time. In that way, you are bound/linked continually with Father God, and with His Child too.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hyiooi ... patri: Putting the Father"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">hyiooi ... patri: Putting the Father first makes for straightforward syntax; putting the Son first leads to a grammatical tangle, because you need to say whose boy. LITERALLY: Let what you have heard from the beginning remain in you. If what you have heard from the beginning remains in you, you will remain in the Son and in the Father too.<span class="Italic">(24)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="25" />Aa Nèngu unu Na ka dhu padhadha le dènge èdhi, peka na, pe èdhi mamuri taa-taa dènge Ne.<bt>And He himself has already promised2 us-inc that we will live forever with Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="epaggelia: promise LITERALLY: And this is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">epaggelia: promise LITERALLY: And this is the promise which he promised us, eternal life.<span class="Italic">(25)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="26" />Ja'a suri sasuri ne, sèna ka miu tadhe dhèu dhu neo leko-monya miu.<bt>I write this letter so that you-pl can/will know/recognise the people who want to deceive (doublet) you.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: I have written these things"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: I have written these things to you about the ones who deceive you.</Message></Annotation><v n="27" />Miu sèmi mere le Roh Mola-Mèci Lamatua, aa miu mamuri pa'èki le dènge Nèngu kahèi. De miu parluu heka dhèu leo aj'a-nori hari miu. Te Roh Lamatua nia le, lula Nèngu ka dhu bisa aj'a aa'i-aa'i dhu lèke. Roh ne kapod'e-kabèli boe, sèmi dhèu leko-monya sèra. De kèpe pa'èra-èra mi ngaa dhu Nèngu nori le, ho miu mamuri d'ara èci taruu dènge Kristus.<bt>You-pl have already received God2's Clean/Holy Spirit, and you also already live bound/linked with Him. So (consequently), you don't need other people to teach (doublet) you anymore. Cuz (elaboration) God2's Spirit is already enough/sufficient, because He can teach everything which is true/correct. He doesn't twist-turn (deceive), like those habitual deceivers2 (doublet). So (consequently), hold firmly to what He has already taught2, so.that you can continue to live one insides with Kristus. [Ex. Summ]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And the annointing which you"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And the annointing which you received from him remains in you, and you do not have need for anyone to teach you. But his annointing teaches you about all things, and is true, and is not a lie. Just as it has taught you, remain in him.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="28" />De sèmi ne'e ana-ana! Miu hud'i mamuri pa'èki taruu dènge Kristus. Sèna ka ropa Na mai hari, miu madha'u boe, aa dènge boe d'ara makae lami titu ètu madha Na.<bt>It's like.this, children! You must live continually bound/linked with Kristus. So that when He comes back again, you will not be afraid and won't be embarrassed/ashamed to stand in front of Him. [KeyT: Key term for 'remain' idop satu hati tarús ~ ta'ika ]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="menete: in the Gospel it's &quot;stay"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">menete: in the Gospel it's "stay tight" for menein. But "stick" may include more of an initiative, an "stay tight" a description of the relationship, so "stick" is probably best here. phanerootheei: usually rendered elsewhere as "come back" when it refers to Jesus's second coming<span class="Italic">(28) (28) </span>LITERALLY: And now, little children, remain in him, so that when he appears we may have confidence, and not be ashamed before him at his coming.</Message></Annotation><v n="29" />Lula miu dhu me'a le, na, Nèngu tao dhoka ngaa dhu lèke, nèti èèna ka bisa me'a kahèi, peka na, dhèu aa'i-aa'i, ladhe tao ngaa dhu lèke, rèngu j'aj'i ana-ana Lamatua.<bt>Because you already know that He always does what is correct/true, that is why you can also know that all people who do according to what is true/correct, they also be/become God2's children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: If you know that he"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: If you know that he is righteous, you know that everyone who does what is right has been born from him.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Dhèu dhu j'aj'i ana-ana Ama Lamatua, hud'i mamuri ku dènge mola<bt>People who become/became God's children must live straight/right</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head 2" usfm="s2">Ana-ana Lamatua mamuri heka dènge tao sala  [\s2]<bt>God2's children don't live doing wrong anymore [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="3" />
      <v n="1" />Miu pajiko sèku sasue Ama ètu sorga mi dedha èdhi! Te sasue Na kapai titu kèna, toke Na ded'e nare èdhi j'aj'i ana-ana Nèngu. Lèke si! Te ngaa dhèu dhu mamuri madhutu dad'èi rai-haha, re'a boe, na, èdhi se cee, lula rèngu tadhe boe Ama Lamatua.<bt>You-pl try and have a think about the love of Father in heaven for us! Cuz (elaboration) that love of His, is so great/amazing, to.the.point.that He raised/elevated/appointed/adopted us-inc to be/ become His children. That's true! But people living according to the desires of the world, don't understand who we-inc are, because they don't know/aren't.acquainted.with God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hina: result, not reason esmen: reality,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">hina: result, not reason esmen: reality, not just a true statement<span class="Italic">(1) (1) </span>LITERALLY: See what kind of love the Father has given us that we should be called children of God; and we are. For this reason the world does not know us, because it did not know him.</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:1" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 1:12</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="2" />Ana-ana pasue! Èdhi j'aj'i le ana-ana Ama Lamatua, te ngaa te'a tare mèka, bèli-camèd'a èdhi j'aj'i sèmi ngaa sa. Dhu te'a, sèmi ne'e ka: bèli-camèd'a ropa Kristus mai hari, èdhi j'aj'i sama sèmi Nèngu kahèi, lula èdhi ladhe tèdhi Nèngu iia-iia.<bt>Beloved children! We-inc have already become God's children, but it is not yet clear how/what else we will become. What we know is like.this: when Kristus comes back in the future, we-inc also will become like Him, because we can see Him clearly/openly. [CHECK UNS: iia-iia]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="èdhi ladhe tèdhi Nèngu dènge iia-iia."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z">èdhi ladhe tèdhi Nèngu dènge iia-iia. = secara jelas</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Beloved, now we are children"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Beloved, now we are children of God, and it has not been shown what we shall be. We know that when he appears, we will be like him, because we will see him just as he is.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu tatae mamai Kristus, tatu ra pamèu mamuri rèngu, sèna ka mamuri ra mola-mèci sama sèmi Kristus.<bt>Everyone who is awaiting/anticipating Kristus' coming, surely they will make their lives clean/holy, in.order.to live clean/holy (doublet) like Kristus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And everyone who has this"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And everyone who has this hope in him purifies himself, just as that one is pure.</Message></Annotation><v n="4" />Sasala aa'i-aa'i ra ka dhu sisu paredha Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu tao sala, sisu paredha Ama Lamatua aa palab'a dènge Ne.<bt>All wrong is violating God2's command/s. That's why all people who have done wrong, have violated God's command/s, and opposed/resisted/rebelled against Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="poioon teen hamartian: generic, not a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">poioon teen hamartian: generic, not a list. No "da" needed. LITERALLY: Everyone who commits sin breaks the law, because sin is breaking the law.<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Miu me'a le, peka na, Kristus j'aj'i dhèu rai-haha sèna ka saku eele sasala-sasigo èdhi. Nèngu bisa tao j'ara èèna, lula Nèngu mesa Na tao nèdhi boe sasala.<bt>You already know that Kristus became human to wipe/erase away our-inc wrongs (doublet). He was able to do that, because He himself had never done wrong.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And you know that that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And you know that that one appeared to take away sins, and there is no sin in him.</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:5" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 1:29</note><v n="6" />De dhèu dhu mamuri pa'èki taruu dènge Ne, mamuri heka dènge tao sala. Te ngaa ladhe dhèu loe boe ad'u-ue sasala, sasoa na, nèngu tadhe boe aa pa'èki boe dènge Kristus.<bt>So (consequently), people who live bound/linked continually with Him, don't live doing wrong anymore. But if a.person lives not ceasing to do wrong, it means that s/he doesn't know/be.acquainted.with and isn't bound/linked with Kristus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Everyone who remains in him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Everyone who remains in him does not continue to sin. Everyone who continues to sin has not seen him or known him.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ana-ana pasue! Baku lèke tipu. Te dhèu dhu mamuri madhutu ngaa dhu lèke, nèngu dhèu d'ara mola èci èèna ka dènge Kristus.<bt>Beloved children! Don't be deceived. Cuz (elaboration) the person who lives according to what is true/correct, s/he is a straight insides (righteous/just) person, like Kristus.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teknia: as if they were his"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">teknia: as if they were his own children ho poioon teen dikaiosyneen dikaios estin: if dikaios is mainly focused on correct behavior in this letter, which it probably is, then we have to work around a tautology in Pidgin.<span class="Italic">(7) (7) </span>LITERALLY: Children, do not let anyone deceive you. The one who does righteousness/justice is righteous/just, just as he is righteous/just.</Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu mamuri ad'u-ue sasala, j'aj'aj'i ra nèti dhèu aae nidhu. Te dhèu aae nidhu ne, baki nèti bhabhelu-katub'a karèi nèti uru j'ara ka. Nèti èèna ka, Ana Ama Lamatua mai ho dhedhe palaho bhabhelu nèti dhèu aae nidhu.<bt>But a person who lives doing wrong, those origins are from the evil spirits' king. Cuz (elaboration) the king of evil spirits is the grandfather of evil (doublet) from the very beginning. That's why God's Child came to destroy the evil of that evil spirit (=Devil). [NOTE to daughter translations: CHECK if last "evil spirit" actually tracks to evil spirit's boss for the UNS's.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="poioon: generic, “keeps on practicing (sin)”"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">poioon: generic, “keeps on practicing (sin)” lyseei ta erga tou diabolou: in general, not specifically in the life of one person, though it starts there<span class="Italic">(8) (8) </span>LITERALLY: The one who sins is of the Devil, because from the beginning the Devil has sinned. For this the Son of God appeared, to destroy the works of the Devil.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="9" />Dhèu dhu j'aj'i le ana Lamatua mamuri heka tao sala, lula Lamatua dhu pea le ètu d'ara nèngu. Nèngu bisa heka ad'u-ue sasala taruu, lula j'aj'aj'i na nèti Lamatua.<bt>A person who has already become God2's child doesn't live doing wrong anymore, because God2 is living in his/her insides. S/He can no longer do wrong continually, because his/her origins/birth is from God2.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Everyone who has been born"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Everyone who has been born from God does not continue to sin, because his seed remains in him, and he cannot sin, because he has been born from God.</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Dènge j'ara ne'e, èdhi bisa tadhe mèu, cee ka dhu j'aj'i nèti Lamatua, aa cee ka dhu mai nèti dhèu aae nidhu. Te dhèu dhu madhutu boe j'ara dhu lèke, aa dhu sue boe a'ari na, sasoa na, j'aj'aj'i na nèti boe Ama Lamatua.<bt>In that.way, we-inc can know who is born/sourced from God2, and who comes from the evil spirits' king. Cuz (elaboration) a person who doesn't do according to what is correct/true, and a person who doesn't love his/her sibling, that means that s/he is not sourced/born from God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kabhia na = turunan"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z">kabhia na = turunan</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By this is shown the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By this is shown the difference between the children of God and the Children of the Devil: Everyone who does not do righteousness is not from God, nor the one who does not love his brother.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-ana Ama Lamatua hud'i pasue ku èci dènge èci [\s2]<bt>God's children must love each other [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Karèi nèti uru ka, miu tadèngi le lii moa dhu peka na, &lt;&lt;Pasue èci dènge èci!&gt;&gt;<bt>From long ago you-pl have already heard this message/instruction which says, &lt;&lt;Love each other!&gt;&gt;</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="anggelia: i.e. the message brought by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">anggelia: i.e. the message brought by an /anggelos/ “messenger” LITERALLY: Because this is the message which you heard from the beginning, that we should love each other.<span class="Italic">(11)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="3:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 13:34</note><v n="12" />Miu sanèd'e era lii lolo Kaen dènge Habel, si? Baku tao madhutu Kaen, te nèngu ne dhèu bhelu-katub'a, ka nèngu pamadhe ari na, Habel. Nga tao ka nèngu tao sèmi èèna? Lula Kaen tao j'ara-j'ara dhu bhelu, te ngaa ari na tao j'ara-j'ara dhu mola.<bt>You still remember Kaen and Habel's story, right? Don't do like Kaen, cuz (elaboration) he was an evil (doublet) person, and he killed his younger sibling Habel. Why did he do like.that? Because he did (various) things which were evil, but his younger.sibling did (various) things which were straight/correct/true.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="poneera: generic; Gk is not /diabolos/"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">poneera: generic; Gk is not /diabolos/ but /poneiros/ ‘the evil one” here; most commentators feel John is deliberate in using a different term here dikaia: also generic, but "da" is part of a set phrase here.<span class="Italic">(12) (12) </span>LITERALLY: Not like Cain who was from the Evil One and murdered his brother. And for what did he murder him? Because his deeds were evil, but his brother's were righteous.</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Lii Lolo dhu Uru Tèka 4:8</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />A'ari aa'i-aa'i! Baku malaa ladhe dhèu dhu madhutu dad'èi rai-haha d'èi boe miu.<bt>Siblings! Don't be surprised/amazed/confused if/when people who follow the world's desires don't like you-pl. [NOTE: no good word for ‘hate’]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ei: factual -- they're going to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">ei: factual -- they're going to hate you anyway LITERALLY: And do not be surprised, brothers, if the world hate you.<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Èdhi te'a le dhu peka na, dhèu dhu mamuri ètu d'ara sasala, ladhe madhe, nèngu cèri eele nèti Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa, lula èdhi pasue dènge a'ari èdhi, èèna j'aj'i mi tadha, peka na, ropa èdhi madhe, èdhi mamuri taruu dènge Lamatua. Te, ladhe dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri dènge boe sasue, bèli-camèd'a madhe, na, rèngu pakaj'èu nèti Ama Lamatua.<bt>We-inc know it is said a person who lives in wrong/sin, when s/he dies, s/he is separated off from God. But because we-inc love our sibling/s, that shows a sign/evidence that, when we die, we will live forever with God2. Cuz (elaboration) if/when all people who do not live in love later die, they will be separated2 away from God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Dead as &quot;no longer among the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">Dead as "no longer among the living" probably needs to be translated differently from dead as "subject to eternal damnation". "Cut off from God" seems to fit most contexts. LITERALLY: We know that he have passed out of death into life, because we love the brothers. The one who does not love remains in death.<span class="Italic">(14)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="3:14" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 5:24</note><v n="15" />Te dhèu dhu sue boe a'ari na, nèngu cakaraa dènge dhèu dhu pamadhe dhèu. De me'a le, na, dhèu dhu sèmi sèra sa, abhu boe mamuri taruu dènge Ama Lamatua.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the person who does not love his/her sibling, s/he is like a person who murders people/person. So (consequently), you already know that people like.that do not obtain eternal life with God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="anthroopoktonos: predicate position paas anthroopoktonos: murderers"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">anthroopoktonos: predicate position paas anthroopoktonos: murderers in general.<span class="Italic">(15) (15) </span>LITERALLY: Everyone who hates his brother is a murderer, and you know that no murderer has eternal life remaining in him.</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Èdhi bisa te'a conto sasue dhu lèke nèti Kristus. Te Nèngu sue èdhi, ka soro ngi'u Na, sèna ka madhe gati èdhi. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi hud'i soro ngi'u èdhi kahèi bagi a'ari èdhi.<bt>We-inc can know the example of correct/true love from Kristus. Cuz (elaboration) He loved us, and He handed over His self/body and died, in.order.to replace/substitute for us. Because of that, we also must hand.over ourselves for our siblings.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="egnookamen: have come to know love"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">egnookamen: have come to know love LITERALLY: By this we know love, because that one laid down his life for us, and we ought to lay down our lives for the brothers.<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Ladhe abhu dhèu dhu unu d'ai, nèdhi a'ari na ca dhèu dhu mamuri susa, te ngaa na tao boe madha-dhilu mi dhèu susa ne, na, tasamia ka nèngu peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a sue Ama Lamatua!&gt;&gt; Lèke boe!<bt>If there is a person who lives sufficiently (=not in poverty), then s/he sees a sibling who is living in difficulty, but doesn't place eyes-ears (Idiom: attend to needs of/show mercy/compassion to) the person in difficulty, how can s/he speak, saying, &lt;&lt;I love God1!&gt;&gt; [He/she] can't!</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: But whoever has the world's"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: But whoever has the world's possessions, and sees his brother in need, and closes his heart against him, how does the love of God remain in him?</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Ana-ana pasue! Baku dhoka sue ètu hèb'a di, te ngaa tao j'ara dhu be'a, ho pad'elo sasue dhu lèke.<bt>Beloved children! Don't just love in the mouth (=with words), but also do good things, to show love which is true/correct.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="meeagapoomen: exhortation, but a generic or"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">meeagapoomen: exhortation, but a generic or impersonal presentation is more congenial in Pidgin for enunciating a principle. Take out the "we"s LITERALLY: Children, let us not love in word nor speech but in deed and truth.<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="re dara lii padhai dhu mènyi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z">re dara lii padhai dhu mènyi di,</Message></Annotation><v n="19" />Te, ladhe èdhi pad'elo sasue dènge ad'u-ue j'ara dhu be'a sèmi èèna, èdhi te'a, na, èdhi abhu mamuri dhu lèke. Dènge sèmi èèna, èdhi madha'u heka, aa èdhi bisa doa kètu ropa èdhi ara lati asa madha Ama Lamatua.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) if we-inc show love and do good things like.that, we know that we are living true/correct. In.that.way, we don't need to afraid, and we can lift our faces (justifiable pride) when we face/report/front up from summons to God. [NLT]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ara = jalan menuju"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z">ara = jalan menuju</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="emprosthen autou: in God's view of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">emprosthen autou: in God's view of us? when we come before him in prayer? The latter is narrower than "emprosthen" usually is, though it might lead neatly into 21-22. LITERALLY: And in this we know that we are of the truth, and reassure our hearts before him.<span class="Italic">(19)</span></Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="boti kètu"><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-18 04:01:31Z" status="Anyone">action of lifting head ; doa kètu = head up with confidence ; doa2 = burp, belch</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Masi ka d'ara iiki èdhi galaa èdhi lula-nèti j'ara dhu lèke boe dhu èdhi ad'u-ue uru èèna, èdhi madha'u ia ka. Te rasa kasia Ama Lamatua kapai risi nèti rasa kasia èdhi. Aa Nèngu dhu ne'a aa'i mèu-mèu kahèi.<bt>Even though our-inc small insides (conscience) accuses us about things that are not right/correct which we have previously done, we don't need to be afraid/fearful. Cuz (elaboration) God's feeling of pity/mercy is so much more than ours feeling of pity/mercy. And He also knows everything.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kataginooskei: this continues v. 19. We"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">kataginooskei: this continues v. 19. We really are OK with God, but thinking about our past sins ties us in knots. Knowing that we really are God's people is a major theme in 1 John. LITERALLY: Because whenever our hearts condemn us, God is greater than our hearts, and he knows everything.<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ana-ana pasue! Ladhe d'ara iiki èdhi galaa boe èdhi, na, èdhi bisa bani aa makae boe, ropa èdhi ara lati asa madha Ama Lamatua.<bt>Beloved children! If/when our-inc small insides don't accuse us, na, we can have confidence and don't need to be ashamed/embarrassed, when we come face/report/front up from summons to God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="parreesian: confidence, not righteousness pros: not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">parreesian: confidence, not righteousness pros: not quite "emprosthen"; you have "parreesian pros" somebody you have a relationship of confidence with. So even if "emprosthen" in 19 comes through as "when we pray" (it could as easily be "when we are called on the carpet"), it's not certain that "pros" is in the same relation to "parreesian" as "emprosthen" is to "peithoo". On the other hand, John could have switched terms just to keep from boring his readers; they're certainly in the same ball park, and "pros" leads to "aitoomen" in the next verse.<span class="Italic">(21) (21) </span>The sentence kind of rolls along, and it's hard to chop it into typically short Pidgin sentences because then a bunch of connectors have to be fitted and the continuity gets jerky. Pidgin occasionally does this, but it's rare. LITERALLY: Beloved, whenever our heart does not condemn us, we have confidence before God.<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="22" />Lula èdhi tao madhutu paredha Lamatua, aa pakarej'e d'ara Na, nèti èèna ka èdhi bisa abhu ngaa aa'i-aa'i dhu èdhi manèngi nèti Nèngu.<bt>Because we-inc do according to God2's commands, and make His insides happy, that's why we can receive/obtain all things which we request from Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And whatever we ask we"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And whatever we ask we receive from him, because we keep his commands, and do what is pleasing before him.</Message></Annotation><v n="23" />Lii paredha Na sèmi ne'e ka: parcaya taruu Ana Na Yesus Kristus, dhu Nèngu pua mai. Aa baku loe pasue èci dènge èci, sama sèmi lii paredha Yesus.<bt>His command is like.this: continually believe in His Child Yesus Kristus, whom He has sent. And don't stop loving each other, like what Yesus commanded. [EXEG: just as he: "he" = Yesus. Ex. Summ #1]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And this is his command:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And this is his command: that we believe in the name of his Son Jesus Christ and love each other, just as he gave us a command.</Message></Annotation><note reference="3:23" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 13:34, 15:12, 17</note><v n="24" />Dhèu dhu tao madhutu lii paredha Ama Lamatua sèra, mamuri na pa'èki dènge Ne, aa Ama Lamatua pa'èki dènge ne kahèi. Èdhi te'a, na, Ama Lamatua ètu d'ara èdhi, lula Roh Na mamuri ètu d'ara èdhi.<bt>A person who does according to God's commands, s/he lives bound/linked with Him. And God is also bound/linked with him/her. We-inc know God is in our insides, because His Spirit is living in our insides. [NLT]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Everyone who keeps his commands"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Everyone who keeps his commands remains in him and he in him. By this we know that he remains in us, by the Spirit he has given us.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Ana-ana Ama Lamatua hud'i mage-mage ku, sèna ka baku lèke tipu [\s2]<bt>God's children must be careful so they are not deceived [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="4" />
      <v n="1" />Ana-ana pasue! Baku lèka leli lii padhai ladhe dhèu mai, peka na, nèngu nèti lii moa Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa miu hud'i dadoo ne paie-iie, ho me'a mèu lii padhai na tare'a-re'a nèti Lamatua, do aad'o. Te limuri ne, ae le dhèu kapod'e-kabèli dhu kako pale-lème rai-haha ne. Dhèu se tipu dhèu, peka na, rèngu sèra dhèu rèti lii padhai Ama Lamatua.<bt>Beloved children! Don't just accept/agree stupidly (=accept 'blindly', without thinking), if a person says s/he is bringing a message from God. But you-pl must carefully evaluate it to find out if what s/he is saying, is truly coming from God2, or not. Cuz (elaboration) now there are already many twister-turners (=deceivers) who walk (=do their work) all.around/over this world. They deceive2 people saying, they are God's spokesperson. [EXEG: /pneumati/: "spirits" as used here is not neccessarily a cosmological being (and it would be difficult to say which one); CEV, TN, TH, "spirit of man." the seat or source of man's insight, feeling, and will. Ex.Summ.#3.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Beloved, do not trust every"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Beloved, do not trust every spirit, but test the spirits to see if they are from God, because many false prophets have gone out into the world.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Èdhi bisa te'a mèu lii moa dhu tare'a-re'a mai nèti Roh Lamatua, dènge j'ara sèmi ne'e: Ama Lamatua padhadha tèke le karèi nèti uru ka, sèna ka neo hia Ana Na mai asa rai-haha ne. Ladhe dhèu dhu nèti lii moa èèna mangaku, peka na, Yesus Kristus èèna tare'a-re'a Ana Ama Lamatua, dhu j'aj'i dhèu rai-haha sama sèmi èdhi, na, lii moa èèna mema nèti Lamatua.<bt>We-inc can know/recognize messages which truly come from God2's Spirit, in this way: God already promised beforehand long ago to send His Child to this world. If the person who brings that message confesses/acknowledges that Yesus Kristus [+known ref] is truly God's Child who became human like us-inc, na, that message of his/hers, really comes from God2.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By this you know the"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By this you know the Spirit of God: every spirit that confesses that Jesus Christ came in the flesh is from God,</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu mangaku boe Yesus sèmi èèna, nèngu mai boe nèti Ama Lamatua. Te èèna mai nèti dhu lab'a Kristus. Miu tadèngi le dhu peka na, dhu lab'a Kristus èèna, bèli-camèd'a cèu mai. Madhutu mola-mola na, dhu sèmi èèna abhu le ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>But a person who doesn't acknowledge Yesus like.that, s/he doesn't come from God. Cuz (elaboration) that comes from (the one) who/those who/that which oppose/s Kristus. You have already heard that, the one/those who/that which oppose/s Kristus, will later appear. In actual fact, one/s like that are already present in this world. [NOTE: "spirit of antichrist" unmarked for number in KM, and unmarked for specificity in both Gk and KM; Nyland, The Source; many commentators gloss this without (the) before antichrist here to indicate its broad scope in the Gk.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: and every spirit that does"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: and every spirit that does not confess Jesus is not from God. This is the spirit of (the) antichrist, whom you have heard that he/it is coming, and now he/it is already in the world.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="4" />Ana-ana pasue! Miu se, mema mai nèti Ama Lamatua, aa koasa Na ètu d'ara miu. Nèti èèna ka, miu segi le dhèu dhu lab'a Lamatua. Te Roh Na dhu pea ètu d'ara miu, èra risi nèti koasa dhu ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>Beloved children! You-pl there, really do come from God, and His power/authority is in your insides. That's why you have defeated/overcome those who oppose God2. Cuz (elaboration) His Spirit that lives/stays/dwells in your insides, is more strong/powerful than the power that is in this world. [EXEG: purposefully leaving unspecified who the he is, that is in the world. Msg, TH, TN, this is talking about power in this verse.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: You are from God, little"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: You are from God, little children, and you have defeated them, because he who is in you is greater than he who is in the world.</Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Dhèu dhu lab'a Lamatua sèra, j'aj'aj'i ra nèti rai-haha. Nèti èèna ka, lii padhai lii ra pa'èki mèno madhutu dad'èi rai-haha. Hèia dhèu rai-haha ne d'èi nanene si.<bt>[As for them] they [are] sourced/born from the world. That's why what they say is also bound up tightly with the desires of this world. So/Thus people in this world like to listen to them.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="pa'èki pamèno = terikat"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z">pa'èki pamèno = terikat</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="autoi: the only antecedent available is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">autoi: the only antecedent available is "spirits". V. 6 is still talking about spirits. LITERALLY: They are from the world. Because of this what they say is from the world and the world listens to them.<span class="Italic">(5)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="6" />Te ngaa j'aj'aj'i èdhi nèti Ama Lamatua. Nèti èèna ka, dhèu dhu tadhe Lamatua d'èi nanene lii padhai èdhi. Te ngaa dhèu dhu mai boe nèti Lamatua, ro'o boe nanene lii padhai èdhi. Dènge j'ara ne'e, ladhe dhèu peka na, nèngu nèti lii moa Lamatua, bisa te'a mia ka dhu lèke dhu mai nèti Roh Lamatua, aa mia ka dhu kapod'e-kabèli.<bt>But we-inc are sourced/born from God2. That's why people who know God2 want to listen to what we say. But people who do not come from God2, they don't want to listen to us. In that.way, if a person says s/he is bringing a message from God2, we can know which (of options) is correct/true, that comes from God2's Spirit, and which is twisted-turned (=deceptive/false). [DISCOURSE: explication for high-level cohesion.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: We are from God. The"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: We are from God. The one who knows God listens to us. The one who is not from God does not listen to us. By this we know the Spirit of truth and the spirit of lying.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Sasue dènge Parcaya -- Sasue èèna, ngaa? [\s2]<bt>Love and Faith -- What is Love? [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="7" />Ana-ana pasue! Èdhi hud'i pasue ku èci dènge èci, lula kapua sasue nèti Ama Lamatua. Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu mamuri pasue mai nèti Ama Lamatua kahèi, aa ra tadhe mèu Ne.<bt>Beloved children! We-inc must love each other, because love is rooted/grounded/based in God. All people who live in mutually love, they also come from God, and know Him well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Nestle 26 sets this whole passage"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">Nestle 26 sets this whole passage as poetry. The first quatrain scans pretty well, but the rest is kind of helter-skelter, and some translations set it as if it were not conscious verse. LITERALLY: Beloved, let us love each other, because love is from God, and everyone who loves has come from God and knows God.<span class="Italic">(7)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="8" />Te ngaa dhèu dhu dènge boe sasue tadhe boe Lamatua. Lula Lamatua èèna, nuka sasue.<bt>But a.person who does not have love, s/he does not know God2. Because God2 [+known ref], is love.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: The one who does not"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: The one who does not love does not know God, because God is love.</Message></Annotation><v n="9" />Lamatua pad'elo sasue Na mi èdhi sèmi ne'e: Na pua Ana Na dhu dhodhoka ca Dhèu èèna ka, mai asa rai-haha ne sèna ka bhoke j'ara hia èdhi. Dènge j'ara sèmi èèna, èdhi bisa mamuri taruu dènge Lamatua.<bt>God2 shows/ed His love to us-inc like.this: He sent His one-and-only Child to come to this world, to open the way for us. In that way, we can live forever with God2.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By this the love of"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By this the love of God is demonstrated among us, because God sent his one and only Son into the world that we might live through him.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ana Na dhodhoka ca dhèu, Ama"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z">Ana Na dhodhoka ca dhèu, Ama Lamatua pua mai asa rai-haha ne,</Message></Annotation><v n="10" />Ladhe neo me'a sasue dhu lèke tare'a, baku pasoro sasue èdhi dènge sasue Lamatua. Te ngaa ladhe sasue Lamatua mi dedha èdhi, lula Ama Lamatua pua Ana Na mai, ho j'aj'i korban sèna ka gati èdhi. Dènge j'ara ne'e, Lamatua saku eele sasala-sasigo èdhi, sèna ka èdhi bisa pabe'a hari dènge Nèngu.<bt>If [you] want to know real/true love, don't compare our-inc love for God2's. But look at God2's love for us, because He sent His Child coming, to become a sacrifice to replace us. With that He erased away our wrongs (doublet), so that we can be in a reciprocally.good.relationship again with Him [NOTE: in a reciprocally good relationship: explicating result of sacrifice as in the Message. "again" is simply implying a former state with a damaged relationship.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: This is what love is,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: This is what love is, not that we loved God, but that he loved us, and sent his Son as a substitute sacrifice for our sins.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="11" />Ana-ana pasue! Lula Ama Lamatua sue èdhi seli eele, na, èdhi hud'i pasue ku èci dènge èci kahèi.<bt>Beloved children! Because God has loved us exceedingly like.that, na, we also must love each other.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Beloved, since God loved us"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Beloved, since God loved us like that, we also ought to love each other.</Message></Annotation><v n="12" />Abhu boe ca dhèu sa dhu ladhe nèdhi mèu Ama Lamatua. Masi ka sèmi èèna, te ngaa ladhe èdhi pasue èci dènge èci, sasoa na, Ama Lamatua bera-bera dènge èdhi. Aa sasue Na asa tabha ètu d'ara mamuri èdhi, toke j'aj'i sasue dhu kateme.<bt>There is not a single person who ever has seen God clearly. Even though it's like that, nevertheless if we love each other, it means God is together with us. And His love increases in our lives, until becoming love which is whole/complete/perfect. [NLT]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="tetheatai: has had a good look"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">tetheatai: has had a good look at God (in Genesis several people saw him in disguise, and in Exodus he says he allowed himself to be seen). LITERALLY: No one has ever seen God. If we love each other, God stays among us, and his love is made perfect among us.<span class="Italic">(12)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="4:12" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 1:18</note></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ama Lamatua pangèd'u le Roh Na ètu d'ara èdhi. Nèti èèna ka, te'a, na, èdhi mamuri d'ara èci dènge Ne, aa Nèngu mamuri d'ara èci dènge èdhi kahèi.<bt>God has given/put/entrusted His Spirit in our-inc insides. That's why we know that, we live one insides (idiom: in.unity/ harmony/ accord) with Him, and He also is one insides with us.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="en toutooi: cataphoric &quot;dis&quot; refers to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">en toutooi: cataphoric "dis" refers to something not filled in yet. "Dat" or "Dass" would be anaphoric, pointing back to verse 12. menomen: "stay tight" is a little more stative, "stick wit" a little more active. Here it's talking about the relationship that exists, not about our action in taking it, so it's stative.<span class="Italic">(13) (13) </span>TERM: Though the idea of a spirit being "inside" somebody is not impossible, the usual way of talking about the phenomenon is with "take ova" or "stay in charge a". The inverse is "let um go". In lexical function terms, the locus of "take ova" where spirits are concerned is "inside", but "take ova" is the primary lexeme. LITERALLY: By this we know that we remain in him and he in us, because he has given us his Spirit.<span class="Italic">(13)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="14" />Ja'a dènge angalai ja'a ngèdhi le Ana Ama Lamatua dènge musi madha ji'i. Ka ji'i peka palème dènge dhèu aa'i-aa'i, na, Ama Lamatua hia le Ana Na mai, sèna ka patabuli dhèu ètu rai-haha ne nèti koasa sasala-sasigo ra.<bt>Me, and my friends have seen God's Child with our very own eyes. Thus we tell all people, saying, Father God has sent2 His Child, to save2 the people in this world from their wrongs/sins (doublet).</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And we have seen and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And we have seen and testify that the Father sent his Son as Savior of the world.</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Dhèu aa'i-aa'i dhu mangaku, peka na, Yesus, Ana Ama Lamatua, nèngu mamuri pabe'a dènge Ama Lamatua, aa Ama Lamatua pabe'a dènge nèngu kahèi.<bt>All people who acknowledge, that, the Yesus [+known ref], is God's Child, s/he lives in a reciprocally.good.relationship with God, and God also is reciprocally good with him/her. [NOTE: yes, technically this is two reciprocals, but this is how to phrase this point in Dhao.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Whoever confesses that Jesus is"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Whoever confesses that Jesus is the Son of God, God remains in him and he in God.</Message></Annotation><v n="16" />Èdhi te'a kahèi, peka na, Lamatua sue èdhi titu kèna. Nèti èèna ka, èdhi parcaya, Nèngu sue èdhi taruu.<bt>We also know that God2 loves us exceedingly. That's why we believe that later He will also continue to love us. [NLT &amp; others translations also put paragraph break in this verse. TN: "Also we (incl) know well that God loves us, and we trust him to love us all the time."]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">Lamatua sue dhèu rai-haha ne titu kèna. De dhèu dhu mamuri pasue, nèngu mamuri d'ara èci dènge Ama Lamatua, aa Lamatua mamuri d'ara èci dènge nèngu kahèi.<bt>God loves people to the max. So (consequently), the person who is living in reciprocal love (with others), also is living one insides with God, and God2 also one insides with him/her.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="kai ... Ho theos agapee estin:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">kai ... Ho theos agapee estin: the connective at verse 16 and the asyndeton at 16b make Nestle's paragraphing attractive. LITERALLY: And we know and have believed the love which God has for us. God is love, and the one who remains in love remains in God and God remains in him.<span class="Italic">(16)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Aa ladhe èdhi d'ara èci dènge Lamatua, sasue èdhi j'aj'i kateme. Hèia, ropa d'ai lod'o èle ka rai-haha ne, Lamatua parisa mamuri dhèu aa'i-aa'i, na, èdhi madha'u boe ara lati asa madha Na, lula èdhi dhu j'aj'i le sèmi Kristus, lod'o dhu Na mamuri ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>And, if/when we-inc are one insides with God2, na, our love becomes love which is whole/complete/perfect. So, when it is the final day (=end of world), God2 examines all people's lives, na, we don't need to be afraid/be fearful to stand in front of Him, because we have become like/the same as Kristus when He lived on this earth. [NLT]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="en toutooi teteleiootai: this is what"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">en toutooi teteleiootai: this is what it takes to make it complete heemoon: probably inclusive here: "all us guys"<span class="Italic">(17) (17) </span>hina: result, not purpose LITERALLY: By this love has been made perfect with us, that we have confidence on the day of judgment, because just as that one is, we also are in this world.<span class="Italic">(17)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="18" />Ladhe èdhi mamuri pasue, na, èdhi dènge heka d'ara madha'u ciki sa. Te ladhe èdhi pasue dènge mola, èèna nuka sèmi èdhi pakaj'èu eele aa'i le madha'u nèti d'ara èdhi. Ladhe dhèu madha'u, d'ara na susa, lula nèngu madha'u lèke huku. Dhèu ne, nuka sèmi ana iiki dhu ne'a mèka sue dhèu dènge mola.<bt>If we-inc live in mutual love, na, we don't have even a tiny bit of fear. Cuz (elaboration) if we love in a true/real/ideal manner, that is the same as if we have gotten rid of/ distanced ourselves from all the feeling of fear in our insides. If a person is afraid, his/her insides are distressed/troubled, because s/he is afraid of being punished. He/She is like a small child who does not yet know how to love people well.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="3rd singular impersonal, usually subjectless in"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">3rd singular impersonal, usually subjectless in Pidgin, as statement of a principle. Also negative subjects don't communicate. kolasin: punishment<span class="Italic">(18) (18) </span>ou teteleiootai: "not grown up" by itself may get close to "sexually immature" rather than "has a ways to go before he has really developed a loving attitude" LITERALLY: There is no fear in love, but perfect love throws out fear, because fear has to do with punishment, but the one who fears has not been made mature by love.<span class="Italic">(18)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Èdhi pasue, lula Ama Lamatua dhu sue uuru le èdhi.<bt>We-inc love, because God loved us first.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: We love, because he loved"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: We love, because he loved us first.</Message></Annotation><v n="20" />Ladhe dhèu padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ja'a sue Ama Lamatua&gt;&gt;, te ngaa nèngu tèka d'ara dènge a'ari na, nèngu monya di. Te ladhe dhèu sue boe a'ari na dhu ètu katanga madha nèngu, tasamia hari nèngu sue Ama Lamatua dhu nèdhi mèka? Bisa boe, sina ma?<bt>If a person speaks saying, &lt;&lt;I love God,&gt;&gt; but he hates/broods (planning revenge--no good word for hate) his sibling, that person is just lying3. Cuz (elaboration) if a person doesn't love his/her sibling who is right in front of him how can s/he love God whom s/he has not yet ever seen? Can't, right?</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="adelphon: generic for a fellow Christian"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">adelphon: generic for a fellow Christian of either sex LITERALLY: If someone says that he loves God, and hates his brother, he is a liar. Because the one who does not love his brother whom he has seen, cannot love God whom he has not seen.<span class="Italic">(20)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="21" />Te Ama Lamatua unu Na ka dhu papuru paredha, peka na, èdhi baku sue dhodhoka Nèngu di, te ngaa sue ku a'ari èdhi dhèu parcaya sèra.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) God himself has handed down the command, saying, we-inc mustn't just love only Him, but we must also love our fellow believers. [EXEG: NRSV, NLT]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: And this is the command"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: And this is the command we have from him, that the one who loves God should love his brother too.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <c n="5" />
      <v n="1" />Dhèu parcaya aa'i-aa'i dhu peka na, Yesus, tare'a-re'a Kristus dhu Ama Lamatua pua mai, dhèu sèra j'aj'i le ana-ana Ama Lamatua. Te dhèu dhu sue ca dhèu ama, tatu sue ana na kahèi.<bt>All believers say, that Yesus [+known ref], is truly Kristus, whom God sent, [as for them] they have already become God's children. Cuz (elaboration), people who love a person who is a father, s/he also loves his children. [EXEG: The Gk is “the one having given birth” and “the one having been born”, so it is a broader principle than just God the Father and Jesus the Son; it also introduces v.2. NRSV: and everyone who loves the parent loves the child. Also heavy support in Ex.Summ. KM in this context works better with gendered "father" than with ungendered "parent". CONNECTOR: Gk. /kai/ can have a sense of "and furthermore" = elaboration, so KM te.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: Everyone who believes that Jesus"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: Everyone who believes that Jesus is the Christ has been born from God, and everyone who loves the father loves his child too.</Message></Annotation><v n="2" />Ladhe èdhi sue Lamatua, aa sab'a madhutu paredha Na, èèna peka na, èdhi sue ana-ana Lamatua kahèi.<bt>If we love God2 and work according to His command/s, that indicates/demonstrates that we also love God2's children.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: By this we know that"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: By this we know that we love the children of God, when we love God and keep his commands.</Message></Annotation><v n="3" />De ladhe èdhi sue Nèngu, èdhi hud'i tao madhutu ku paredha Na sèra. Aa paredha Na bia boe.<bt>So (consequently), if we love Him, we must do according to His commands. And His commands are not heavy.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="bareiai: heavy, burdensome, load us down."><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">bareiai: heavy, burdensome, load us down. It may be hard, but it's not crushing. LITERALLY: For this is the love of God, that we keep his commands; and his commands are not burdensome.<span class="Italic">(3)</span></Message></Annotation><note reference="5:3" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 14:15</note><v n="4" />Èdhi dhu j'aj'i le ana-ana Lamatua, bisa segi dad'èi rai-haha ne, lula èdhi parcaya Ne.<bt>We who have become God2's children, can conquer/win over the desires of the world, because we believe in Him.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hee pistis heemoon: &quot;trus somebody&quot; LITERALLY:"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">hee pistis heemoon: "trus somebody" LITERALLY: because everyone who is born from God overcomes the world; and this is the victory which overcomes the world: our faith.<span class="Italic">(4)</span></Message></Annotation><v n="5" />Te dhèu dhu segi dad'èi rai-haha, nuka dhèu dhu parcaya, peka na, Yesus, Ana Ama Lamatua.<bt>Cuz (elaboration) the person who can defeat the desires of the world, is the person who believes that Yesus [+known ref], is God's Child.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Generic needs to be expressed by"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">Generic needs to be expressed by the singular here because of "ony." ho pisteuoon hoti: "trus" is probably not the best rendering. "Stay shua"<span class="Italic">(5) (5) </span>LITERALLY: Who is the one who overcomes the world? Only the one who believes that Jesus is the Son of God.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Parcaya Yesus, gaguna na ngaa? [\s2]<bt>Believing in Yesus, what is it useful for? [\s2]</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="6" />Sad'i miu me'a, na, Yesus, dhèu rai-haha kahèi, aa Nèngu ne, Kristus kahèi dhu Ama Lamatua hia mai asa rai-haha ne. Lod'o Nèngu neo pakako sasab'a-la'a Na, Yohanis sarani Ne pake èi. Èle èèna ka, Nèngu madhe aa pasuti raa Na kahèi. De dhu lèke ka, mesa boe èi di dhu Yohanis pake sarani Nèngu, te ngaa raa Na dhu suti eele èèna dhu kab'ua risi. Te Roh Ama Lamatua mesa Na ka dhu peka sèmi èèna, aa dhu ne'a boe leko-monya.<bt>Just so you know. Yesus [+known ref], was both human, cuz (elaboration) He is also Kristus whom God has sent to this world. When He was about to carry out/begin His work, Yohanis *baptised Him using water. After that, He also died and spilled out His blood. So (consequently) what is true/important, is not just the water which Yohanis used to baptise Him, but His blood which spilt out, is more important/valuable. Cuz (elaboration) God's Spirit himself is the one who tells like.that, and He is not capable of twist-turn (=deceive). [EXEG: TH, TN, Ex. Summ.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="en: not &quot;because John baptized him"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">en: not "because John baptized him ... because they killed him" but "referring to the occasion when" LITERALLY: This is the one who comes by water and blood, Jesus Christ. Not by water only, but by water and blood. And the Spirit is the witness, because the Spirit is true.<span class="Italic">(6) (7) </span>LITERALLY: Because there are three things that testify, LITERALLY: the Spirit and the water and the blood. And the three agree.<span class="Italic">(8) (9) </span>LITERALLY: Since we receive the testimony of men, the testimony of God is greater, because it is the testimony of God, which he has testified about his Son. LITERALLY: The one who believes in the Son of God has the testimony in himself; the one who does not believe God, makes God a liar, because he has not believed in the testimony which God testified about his Son.<span class="Italic">(10) (11) </span>LITERAL TRANLATION: And this is the testimony, that God gave us eternal life, and this life is in his Son.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Yesus ne, mesa boe dhèu rai-haha biasa di. Te Nèngu ne, Kristus dhu Ama Lamatua hia mai asa rai-haha kahèi. "><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-18 06:24:14Z" status="Anyone">OV</Message></Annotation><v n="7" />Te abhu tèlu j'ara dhu j'aj'i sakasii:<bt>Cuz (elaboration), there are three things which are witnesses: [EXEG on ftn: TNIV (for date on appearing in translations), NRSV, NLT; but Carson (1979) has it showing up in one or two hand-written margin notes after A.D. 800.]</bt><note reference="5:7" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Abhu Alkitab dhu suri tabha, peka na, [&lt;&lt;(7b) ètu sorga, nuka Ama, Lii Holo-Nori, dènge Roh Mola-Mèci. (8a) Ka tèlu j'ara se, j'aj'i mi èci. Aa abhu tèlu j'ara dhu j'aj'i sakasii ètu rai-haha,&gt;&gt;]. Aa te ngaa, lii se'e abhu boe ètu d'ara sasuri lii Yunani uru tèka. Lii se'e ra suri tabha ètu èci-dua Alkitab leo, karèi nèti abad ka-14.<bt>There are other Bibles that add, saying, [“(7b) in heaven, that is the Father, the Words/Sayings, and the Holy Spirit. (8a) And the three of these are one. And there are three things which are witnesses on earth,”]. Whereas in fact, these words do not exist in the original Yunani language writings. The words were added to the writings in one or two other Bibles beginning from the 14th century.</bt></note><v n="8" />nuka Roh Lamatua, èi dhu Yohanis pake sarani Yesus, aa raa Yesus unu Na. Tèlu j'ara se'e ka, pad'elo ca j'ara dhu sama lula-nèti Yesus.<bt>that is, God2's Spirit, the water which Yohanis used to baptise Yesus, and Yesus' own blood. All three of those things, show/point.out one thing which is the same about Yesus.</bt><v n="9" />Ladhe dhèu rai-haha ka j'aj'i sakasii, na, èdhi bisa parcaya ne. Risi-risi hari ladhe Ama Lamatua unu Na ka dhu j'aj'i sakasii lula-nèti Ana Nèngu unu Na. Aa te ngaa tèlu j'ara se'e dhu Ama Lamatua pake, ho j'aj'i mi tadha dhu peka na, Yesus mesa boe dhèu rai-haha biasa di, te ngaa Nèngu ne Kristus kahèi.<bt>If a human is the one who is a witness, na, we-inc can believe him/her. And especially/even.more.so if God himself is the one who is witness about His own Child. In.actual.fact these three things are what God has used as a sign/evidence that Yesus wasn't just an ordinary human, but He was also Kristus. [EXEG: NLT and CEV missed a couple higher level signals in the Gk. hinted at in Ex. Summ. discussion. so our rendering of last clause not only makes more sense, but also more tightly reflects the Gk. Ex. Summ. + higher-level cohesion]</bt><v n="10" />Dhèu dhu parcaya Ana Ama Lamatua, sasoa na, dhèu ne sèmi nare le Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua, lula-nèti Ana Na. Te ngaa dhèu dhu lèka boe Lamatua, nèngu nuka sèmi dhèu dhu padhai lii, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama Lamatua leko-monya!&gt;&gt; Dènge j'ara ne'e, nèngu sèmi boe Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua lula-nèti Ana Na.<bt>A person who believes in that Child of God's, that means, that person accepted God2's Words about His Child. But a person who doesn't believe2 in God2, s/he is the same as a person who speaks, saying, &lt;&lt;God is is a twister-turner (=deceiver)!&gt;&gt; In that way, s/he does not accept God2's Words about His Child.</bt><v n="11" />Isi nèti Lii Holo-Nori Lamatua nuka sèmi ne'e: Lamatua hia le èdhi mamuri dhu lèke, toke d'ai mia-mia. Aa èdhi abhu mamuri ne, lula èdhi parcaya Ana Na.<bt>The content of God2's Words are like.this: God2 has given us true/real life which goes forever [phrasing from gospel of John]. And we obtain that life, because we believe in His Child.</bt><note reference="5:11" class="Note Cross Reference Paragraph" usfm="x">Yohanis 3:36</note><v n="12" />De dhèu dhu pa'èki dènge Ana Ama Lamatua abhu mamuri toke d'ai mia-mia dènge Ne. Te ngaa dhèu dhu pa'èki boe dènge Ana Ama Lamatua, abhu boe mamuri sèmi èèna.<bt>So (consequently), the person who is bound/linked with God's Child can live forever with Him. But the person who is not bound/linked with God's Child, does not get/obtain that life.</bt></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Nga tao ka Yohanis suri sasuri ne?<bt>Why does Yohanis write this letter?</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="13" />Ja'a suri madha j'ara se'e aa'i-aa'i hia miu dhèu parcaya Ana Ama Lamatua, sèna ka me'a mèu, na, miu unu mamuri toke d'ai mia-mia.<bt>I write all these things to you who believe in God's Child, so that you can truly/really know/understand, that, you obtain/get/have eternal life (nominal interp)/can live forever (verbal interp) [NOTE: Dhao leans slightly toward the nominal reading].</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: I write these things to"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: I write these things to you that believe in the name of the Son of God, so that you may know that you have eternal life.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis suri tabha j'ara-j'ara sabaj'a<bt>Yohanis writes in addition/further about prayer</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="14" />Ladhe èdhi sabaj'a mi Ama Lamatua, sad'i èdhi manèngi ngaa èèna ka madhutu dad'èi Na, èdhi bisa te'a tare'a-re'a, na, Nèngu tadèngi lii manèngi èdhi sèra.<bt>If we-inc pray to God, as long as we request whatever is according to His will/desire, we can be assured/convinced (truly know) that He hears our request. [NOTE to daughter translations: make sure it is “ask what is according to his will” rather than “pray according to his will”, so that the focus is on WHAT we ask for, rather than the magic formula of HOW we ask.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ean: whenever, indefinite kata to theleema"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">ean: whenever, indefinite kata to theleema autou: in line with his plans, not a passive "que sera, sera".<span class="Italic">(14) (14) </span>LITERALLY: And this is the confidence which we have toward him, that whatever we ask according to his will, he hears us.</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="Ladhe èdhi sabaj'a mi Ama Lamatua"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z">Ladhe èdhi sabaj'a mi Ama Lamatua dènge dara kateme, sad'i èdhi manèngi ngaa èèna ka madhutu dadèi Lamatua, na, èdhi te'a tare'a-re'a na Nèngu tadèngi lii manèngi èdhi deo na.</Message></Annotation><v n="15" />Aa ladhe èdhi parcaya tare'a-re'a sèmi èèna, èdhi te'a kahèi, na, èdhi abhu ngaa-ngaa dhu èdhi manèngi nèti Ama Lamatua.<bt>And if we truly believe like.that, we also know that we receive/obtain/get what we request/ask from God.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ean: hypothetic &quot;if&quot;, not factual &quot;since&quot;?"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">ean: hypothetic "if", not factual "since"? Blass-Debrunner-Funk 372.1.a consider this use, which is with the indicative mode, as a vulgar substitution for "ei" or "epei", in which case it could be read as English "since". But the factuality is conveyed by the "if ... den" pair, not by substituting a Pidgin causal for the conditional. LITERALLY: And if we know that he hears us in whatever we ask, we know that we have the things which we asked from him.<span class="Italic">(15)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="16" />Ladhe èu mèdhi a'ari mu tao sala dhu nèti boe mamadhe, be'a risi èu sabaj'a sèna ka Ama Lamatua soru-bara a'ari èu èèna ho na abhu sod'a. A'abhu ja'a sèmi ne'e ka: abhu sasala dhu nèti boe dhèu asa d'ara mamadhe. Abhu kahèi sasala dhu nèti dhèu asa mamadhe. Te ngaa ja'a pua boe miu ho sabaj'a ladhe abhu sasala sèmi èèna.<bt>[CHECK think through implications of last sentence. not pray vs. not pray about that.] If you-sg see/encounter your sibling doing wrong which does not bring death, it's better/best for you to pray requesting God to help (doublet) that sibling of yours, so that s/he lives/is saved. My opinion is like this: there are wrong/s which do not lead people to death. And there are also wrongs which lead people to death. But I am not ordering you-pl to pray if there is wrong like.that. [EXEG (JEG): mee pros thanaton: "leads to death" doesn't specify whether this is physical death or spiritual death. If it's tagged as spiritual, we're bringing up the Scholastic chimaera of man being able to cook up something so heinous that God can't forgive it, which is not too different from asking if God can make a rock so big he can't move it. If it's just physical, then it's the more obvious situation that if you rob a bank and get shot dead, praying for you isn't going to help. The rendering we have is no more and no less explicit than the Greek, and as such puts the ball in the theologians' court where it belongs.] [EXEG: First complication: Gk is “if anyone sees … he (3s) should ask”. English translations (I believe, correctly) render this as “if anyone sees … you (2s/p) should pray…” For genre reasons I believe it is correct in the Timor region lgs to use “If you (2s) see … you (2s) should pray and ask…” vs. 14-15 are in 1pi, but here John is pushing for a specific application. TB is literal to the Gk here (3s in both instances), and it is entirely possible nobody would think of applying it to themselves. Second complication: Do you think it is clearly implied here that God will actually give that person life if they pray for that? In these Timor region lgs, ‘pray’ and ‘ask’ are manipulative verbs. Grammatically they obligatorily take the irrealis complementiser, not the realis complementisor that is available to most other speech act verbs. This is logical, because what is being asked or ordered has not yet been carried out. It is common cross linguistically. So check with the UNSs. I can't think of any other way of phrasing it without making really heavy information load. Dhao has 2 irrealis complementisers that can be used, and the one we've used here seems to imply that the request was fulfilled.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="hamartia: without the article, not a"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">hamartia: without the article, not a specific act, but generic. mee pros thanaton: doesn't specify whether this is physical death or spiritual death. If it's tagged as spiritual, we're bringing up the Scholastic chimaera of man being able to cook up something so heinous that God can't forgive it, which is not too different from asking if God can make a rock so big he can't move it. If it's just physical, then it's the more obvious situation that if you rob a bank and get shot dead, praying for you isn't going to help. The rendering we have is no more and no less explicit than the Greek, and as such puts the ball in the theologians' court where it belongs.<span class="Italic">(16) (16) </span>LITERALLY: If anyone sees his brother commit a sin that does not lead to death, he should pray and God will give him life. I refer to those whose sin does not lead to death. There is a sin that leads to death. I am not saying that he should pray about that.</Message></Annotation><v n="17" />Tatao karehe aa'i-aa'i, sala ètu madha Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa abhu kahèi sasala dhu nèti boe mamadhe.<bt>All bad/evil deeds/behaviour is wrong/sin in God's eyes. But there are also wrongs/sin that do not bring death. [EXEG: against God. 2nd sent "But" from Ex.Sum. &amp; TN]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: All unrighteousness is sin, and"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: All unrighteousness is sin, and there is sin that does not lead to death.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Section Head" usfm="s1">Yohanis pasanèd'e hari j'ara-j'ara dhu kab'ua risi<bt>Yohanis reminds again about the important thing</bt></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="18" />Dhèu dhu pa'èki le dènge Ama Lamatua, mamuri heka tao sala, te Ana Ama Lamatua dhu ladhe-leru ne. Aa dhu bhelu-katub'a bisa boe segi ne kahèi.<bt>A person who is already bound/linked to God doesn't live doing wrong anymore, cuz God's Child is watching.over/guarding (doublet) him/her. And that which is evil (doublet) also cannot win.over/conquer him/ her.</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="sanoro = lindungi"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Anyone">sanoro = lindungi</Message><Message author="Chuck" created="2010-03-18 07:28:53Z" status="Anyone">rare ;</Message></Annotation><Annotation class="General" selectedText="LITERALLY: We know that everyone who"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">LITERALLY: We know that everyone who has been born from God does not continue sinning, but the Son of God keeps him, and the Evil One does not touch him.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="19" />Èdhi te'a, na, èdhi kapua ètu d'ara Ama Lamatua. Te ngaa èdhi te'a kahèi, na, dhu bhelu-katub'a dènge koasa ho ator dhèu aa'i-aa'i ètu rai-haha ne.<bt>We-inc know that we here, are rooted/grounded in God. But we also know that that which is evil (doublet) has the power/authority to oversee/regulate/control all the people in this world. [NLT]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ek tou theou: 2:16 suggests &quot;has"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">ek tou theou: 2:16 suggests "has the quality of". 3:10, 4:4, 4:6 could work with this interpretation, but I'm not sure that "now we same kine jalike God" gives the idea that God has made us be that way and he started it. en tooi poneerooi: This would be ambiguous if not for v. 18, which is ho poneeros, the evil person, rather than "evil" in the abstract, which would be neuter.<span class="Italic">(19) (19) </span>LITERALLY: We know that we are from God, and the whole world lies in wickedness.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="20" />Èdhi te'a, na, Ana Ama Lamatua mai le, sèna ka hia èdhi te'a mèu j'ara se'e, ho èdhi bisa tadhe mèu Ama Lamatua dhu tare'a. Limuri ne, èdhi bisa mamuri pabe'a dènge Ne, lula èdhi mamuri d'ara èci dènge Ana Na, Yesus Kristus. Te Yesus Kristus èèna, tare'a-re'a Lamatua kahèi.<bt>We know that God's Child has come so that we know/understand these things clearly, so that we can know/be.acquainted with the true/real God. Now we are able to live in a reciprocally good relationship with Him, because we live one insides with His Child, Yesus Kristus. Cuz (elaboration) Yesus Kristus is also the true/real God2.</bt><note reference="5:20" class="Note General Paragraph" usfm="f">Sasuri Lii Yunani suri, peka na, &lt;&lt;Ama èèna, θεός (<span class="Italic">theos</span>, nuka Allah).&gt;&gt; Aa &lt;&lt;Ana Na, Yesus Kristus, θεός (<span class="Italic">theos</span>, nuka Allah) kahèi.&gt;&gt;<bt>The Yunani language writings, write, saying, “The Father, is θεός (<span class="Italic">theos</span>, that is Allah)”. And “His Son, Yesus Kristus, is also θεός (<span class="Italic">theos</span>, that is Allah).”</bt></note>Aa Nèngu ka hia dhèu abhu mamuri toke d'ai mia-mia la'e.<bt>And He is the one who enables people to live forever. [NLT: And now we are in God *because* we are in his Son, JC.] [NOTE to daughter translations: the exegesis of the early church fathers used this verse to form the creeds that says Jesus is very God of very God; also TB, HCE, NRSV, NLT, CEV, etc.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="ton aleethinon: because of the rest"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">ton aleethinon: because of the rest of the verse, and the masculine gender, this means the True One or the True God. But "true god" is acrolectal. "Da One dass God fo real kine" is more likely to communicate. en tooi aleethinooi, en tooi hyiooi autou I. Kh.: there's no causal implication in the appositive. It's "related to the True God; specifically, to his Son"<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>autou: antecedent is tooi aleethinooi. houtos: In Greek, refers backward. But "dis" in Pidgin implies that the referent has not been identified yet. So it needs to be "dass" or "dat".<span class="Italic">(20) (20) </span>LITERALLY: We know that the Son of God has come, and has given us understanding so that we know the one who is true. We are in the true one, his Son Jesus Christ. This is the true God and eternal life.</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Paragraph" usfm="p">
      <v n="21" />Ana-ana, ee! J'aga paie-iie mamuri miu. Mage abhu dhu seti eele ho gati Ama Lamatua nèti d'ara miu.<bt>Children, ee! Guard your lives carefully. May it not be that something shoves aside/elbows out of the way to replace God in your insides. [EXEG: idols = take God's place in your heart (NLT); clever facsimile (Message) also TH.]</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="siru = ganti yg tidak asli,"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z">siru = ganti yg tidak asli, tukar dgn palsu</Message></Annotation></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">D'ai sange ne'e ka.<bt>That's all.</bt></p>
    <p class="Line 2" usfm="q2">Nèti ja'a, Yohanis<bt>From me, Yohanis</bt><Annotation class="General" selectedText="teknia: like children to me (old"><Message author="Unknown Author" created="2009-10-05 02:00:21Z" status="Information">teknia: like children to me (old apostle to church leaders) LITERALLY: Little children, guard yourselves from idols.<span class="Italic">(21)</span></Message></Annotation></p>
  </book>
</bible>